          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Old wells, newer ways </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          One of the simplest methods to increase oil production is water flooding, which involves pumping large volumes of water into the reservoir to displace the oil. Then there’s CO₂ injection, where carbon dioxide is injected at high pressure, causing the oil to swell slightly and flow out easily. Another effective method is <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-31-05-2025-refracking?source=website" target="_blank">refracking</a>, where fractures are created using advanced technology to boost oil flow. 
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Hildebrand scaled these methods with precision and aggression. Their wells churn out over 400,000 barrels of oil equivalent every day, rivaling public-traded energy titans. In many cases, it has extended the well’s existence by decades and even increased production beyond projections. But if Hilcorp can turn old wells into currency machines, why can’t ExxonMobil or Chevron do the same? The short answer: they’re not built for it.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Big oil companies are geared toward mega-projects, such as deepwater rigs, shale megafields, and LNG terminals, which deliver massive volumes and even bigger returns. Small, mature wells are a logistical nightmare and aren’t worth the administrative and capital overhead of multinational giants. </p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Barrel boom</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-31-05-2025-in-a-bold-5-billion-move?source=website" target="_blank">In a bold $5.6B move</a>, Hilcorp bought BP’s entire Alaskan business as part of BP’s $10B divestment strategy. The agreement handed over some major assets, including BP’s stake in the Prudhoe Bay oil field (the biggest in the US at one point) and its share of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline. The agreement nearly fell apart when the pandemic crashed oil values, but by 2022, Russia’s invasion of Ukraine sent values soaring past $120 a barrel.</p>
         </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/jackup-rig-drilling-natural-gas-well-hilcorp-tyonek-platform-cook-inlet-2023.jpg" alt="A specialized unit called a jackup rig drilled a natural gas well in 2023 at Hilcorp’s Tyonek platform in Cook Inlet" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>A specialized unit called a jackup rig drilled a natural gas well in 2023 at Hilcorp’s Tyonek platform in Cook Inlet. Credits: Nathaniel Herz for Alaska Public Media
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Under BP, Prudhoe Bay's output had steadily declined from 306,000 barrels every day in 2010 to just 209,000 by 2019. But in Hilcorp’s first year at the helm, production surged by 2.6%, hitting around 224,000 barrels every day. Just like that, Hilcorp became Alaska’s second-biggest oil producer. Hildebrand led multiple other agreements with Chevron, ConocoPhillips, and others to take over "end-of-life" wells.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Hilcorp remains profitable even in low-price environments by operating a lean, technology-driven business with an efficiency-based approach. One of Hilcorp’s most underrated assets is its <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-31-05-2025-work-culture?source=website" target="_blank">work culture</a>. The company operates with a lean hierarchy of no more than five layers between the front-line worker and Hildebrand himself. This structure trims expenses and empowers employees to make real-time decisions on well operations. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         As one of America’s largest privately owned energy producers, Hilcorp continues to shape the future of domestic oil and gas with a bold, employee-driven approach.</p>
          </mj-text> 
